Goal of this project:

We are going to examine the data, find some trends and patterns in the distribution of Satisfaction status on the basis of the other predictors, present some business-metrics, and think about possible reasons for disSatisfaction of the users.

Next, the amount of NAs is just 207 in our dataset, in the variable that describes a delay in minutes. For 62988 records it is a pretty insignificant number, so we remove them.

So, seems like those who own a loyalty card are more likely to be satisfied with our company.

As there are several scores on quality of services based on the clients satisfaction and we can see that satisfied customers tend to be loyal in a higher degree we will make satisfaction the target of our research.

Lets check the relationsip between these two variables statistically:

chisq = chisq.test(data$Loyalty_card, data$Satisfaction)
chisq
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  data$Loyalty_card and data$Satisfaction
## X-squared = 3740.2, df = 1, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
corrplot(chisq$stdres, method = "number", is.cor = FALSE, tl.col = "black")

We observe p-value to be <0.05 and thus be statistically significant: it reports about the ture relationship between these two variables. The corrplot of standartized residuals reports that many more disloyal customers are dissatisfied than it was expected if these variables will be independent - and vice versa.

Hence, we find it logical to construct our predictions for satisfaction of customers. We are going to develop strategies to upper satisfaction status and encourage more customers to be loyal.

colnames(mau) <- "MAU"

Hypothesis

Finally, lets write out the hypothesis on the basis of our exploratory analysis:

The first set of hypothesis includes stable variables that we cannot change, e.g.gender:

  1. As males are positively associated with higher dissatisfaction level, airline services should pay more attention to male audience, e. g. some gender-specific campaigns probably
  2. Women are positively associated with higher level of satisfaction with airline services

The next set of hypothesis is related to changeable variables, e.g.quality of airline services of various type:

  1. Satisfied customers on average make more flights
  2. Online airline services are positively associated with higher level of satisfaction of airline services
  3. Onboard services quality are positively associated with higher level of satisfaction of airline services
  4. Probably after year of 2014 some changes in the company occurred which made the amount of satisfied customers greater. We should explore this change and reveal the pattern

2. Loyalty Uplift Policy

Model #1. Clusterization

So, from the previous step we have found out that difference between state of satisfaction or dissatisfaction lays in:

  • sex
  • amount of flies
  • distance of flight
  • the year of 2014
  • estimation of online services: online support, online booking, and online boarding
  • estimation of on-board services:Cleanliness, on-board service, inflight entertainment, inflight wi-fi, food and drinks, seat comfort, and legroom service
  • estimation of services in the airports: convenience of departure and arrival time, gate location, baggage handling, check-in service

Lets choose the variables to build a mechanism of clusterization with.

We cannot describe the clusters by the date of flight - it is not some metric that we can measure, it is so-called metadata. Sex doesnt suit as clusterization mechanism will be built on numerical data and we wont be able to describe clusters by sex from a numerical perspective.

So, clusters will be built on:

  • amount of flies
  • distance of flight
  • estimation of online services: online support, online booking, and online boarding
  • estimation of on-board services:Cleanliness, on-board service, inflight entertainment, inflight wi-fi, food and drinks, seat comfort, and legroom service
  • estimation of services in the airports: convenience of departure and arrival time, gate location, baggage handling, check-in service
  • and a newly computed variable that depicts difference between last and first flight of a customer - in other words, how long is the customer with us

All the values were rescaled from 0 to 1 for consistency of measurement scale.

data$ddays <- as.numeric(data$last_flight - data$first_flight_date)
library(purrr)
data.scored = data
library(scales)
data.scored$Flight.Distance1 = scales::rescale(data.scored$Flight.Distance, to = c(0, 1))
data.scored$Flight.Count1 = scales::rescale(data.scored$Flight.Count, to = c(0,1))
data.scored$ddays1 = scales::rescale(data.scored$ddays, to = c(0,1))
data.scored$Online.Services1 = scales::rescale(data.scored$online_services, to = c(0,1))
data.scored$On.board.services1 = scales::rescale(data.scored$On.board.service, to = c(0,1))
data.scored$Airport.Services1 = scales::rescale(data.scored$airport_services, to = c(0,1))

We see that all the variables has significant differences among Satisfied and Dissatisfied groups and worth to be included in clusterization.

Lets choose the best amount of cluster with the use of the Elbow plot.

library(purrr)
data.cluster = data.scored %>% dplyr::select(Flight.Distance1, Flight.Count1, ddays1, Online.Services1, On.board.services1, Airport.Services1)

# Use map_dbl to run many models with varying value of k (centers)
tot_withinss <- map_dbl(1:10,  function(k){
  model <- kmeans(x = data.cluster, centers = k)
  model$tot.withinss
})

# Generate a data frame containing both k and tot_withinss
elbow_df <- data.frame(
  k = 1:10,
  tot_withinss = tot_withinss
)

# Plot the elbow plot
 ggplot(elbow_df, aes(x = k, y = tot_withinss)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Number of clusters", y ="Total within-cluster sum of squares",title = "Elbow plot") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:10) + theme_linedraw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=14, hjust = 0.5, face="bold"))

From the number of 1 to 5 a line goes with wide steps, reducing the total within-cluster sum of squares, however after 5 it slows down and these changes become not so big. So, lets assign 5 clusters to the data.

How many observations are here in each cluster after the assignment?

set.seed(111)
clusters <- kmeans(data.scored[,c("Flight.Distance1", "Flight.Count1", "ddays1", "Online.Services1", "On.board.services1", "Airport.Services1")], 5)

Lets estimate how different these clusters represent the data. Estimation is done on the initial 6 variables, dimensionality is downgraded with PCA.

pca <- data.scored %>% dplyr::select(Flight.Distance1, Flight.Count1, ddays, Online.Services1, On.board.services1, Airport.Services1)
pcmp <- princomp(pca)
pred_pc <- predict(pcmp, newdata=pca)[,1:2]
clusters <- data.scored$Cluster
library(data.table)
comp_dt <- cbind(as.data.table(pred_pc), cluster = as.factor(clusters))
ggplot(comp_dt,aes(Comp.1,Comp.2))+ geom_point(aes(color = cluster),size=3, alpha = 0.5) + xlab("PCA1") + ylab("PCA2") + ggtitle("Visual estimation of clusters divergence") + scale_color_brewer(palette = "Pastel1")

We see that the clusters have a good divergence in the 2, 3 and 4 groups, however have some similarity and imposition in 1st and 5th groups. However, weve tried less and more amount of k-means and divergence in groups remained or even became more messy, so weve decided to stay with the number of 5.

Lets dive into exploration further.

# Grouping by the cluster assignment and calculate averages
data.mean <- data.scored %>% dplyr::select(Flight.Distance1, Flight.Count1, ddays1, Online.Services1, On.board.services1, Airport.Services1, Cluster) %>% group_by(Cluster) %>% summarize_if(is.numeric,mean)

# Creating the min-max scaling function
min_max_standard <- function(x) {
  (x - min(x))/(max(x)-min(x))
}

# Applying
data.minmax <- data.mean %>% mutate_if(is.numeric, min_max_standard)

              
# Creating a parallel coordinate plot of the values, starts with column 2
library(GGally)

parrallel_plot = ggparcoord(data.minmax, columns = 2:ncol(data.minmax), 
           groupColumn = "Cluster", scale = "globalminmax")  +
  labs(x = "", y = "",title = "Parallel Coordinate Plot") + theme_linedraw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=14, hjust = 0.5, face="bold")) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 20, vjust = 1, hjust=1))

clusters_satisfaction_plot = plot_xtab(data.scored$Cluster, data.scored$Satisfaction, 
         margin = "row",
         bar.pos = "stack",show.legend = T, show.n = F, coord.flip = T,
          geom.colors = "Pastel1",
         title = "Distribution of Satisfaction based on cluster")

grid.arrange(clusters_satisfaction_plot, parrallel_plot, nrow = 2)

It is interesting that we do not have a group with the majority of satisfied customers - the half is the best result. We have something to work on :)

  • 1-st cluster: about 2/3 of the customers are dissatisfied. They stayed just for a while, has several flights and on medium distances. They have high estimation of online services, however thay poorly rate on board and airport services.
  • 2-nd cluster: we see that about half of the customers are dissatisfied. Ddays is very high, so they stayed long with us, had huge number of flights, fly for short distances, had high estimations of airport services, but were less satisfied with the online and on-board services
  • 3-rd cluster: almost 80% of the customers are disloyal. They were with us for some time, had medium amount of flights and flout on medium distances, dramatically poorly estimated airport services and on-board services, gave a little better estimation for online, but still very poor.
  • 4-th cluster: Approximately 50% of the users are disloyal. They are not long with us, have small amount of flights and distances are short and estimation here is maximum everywhere.
  • 5-th cluster: approximately 2/3 the users are disloyal. They stayed with us for a small time, had several flights for the longest distances, gave high rates for the services by airports and on board, but were extremely dissatisfied with online services.

Uplifting hypothesis: according to this cluster partition, we can uplift all of these segments, but especially 1st, 3rd and 5th clusters - those, who choose to fly on medium and long distances. We have higher chances for it with the 3rd cluster - customers here were for a long time with us, had weighty times of flies with us and may be inclined to come back.

Model 1: Evaluation

Lets check what we can do for each cluster as the uplift policy. Weve used random-forest model from randomforest package.

library(dplyr)
# creating new dataset for random forest
model_data <- data.scored %>% dplyr::select(1:25, Cluster) %>% filter(Cluster==1)
model_data$customer_id <- as.character(seq.int(nrow(model_data)))
model_data <- left_join(model_data, rfm_table, by = "customer_id") %>% na.omit() %>% dplyr::select(-c(27:32), -customer_id, Satisfaction, -Loyalty_card, -Cluster)

# correcting the types of variables
model_data$Gender <- as.factor(model_data$Gender)
model_data$Home.City <- as.factor(model_data$Home.City)
model_data$Class <- as.factor(model_data$Class)
model_data$Satisfaction <- as.factor(model_data$Satisfaction)

# splitting to train and test
library(caret)
set.seed(222)
d_test = createDataPartition(model_data$Satisfaction, p = 0.2, list = FALSE)
data_test = model_data[d_test,]
data_train = model_data[-d_test,]

#training a model
library(randomForest)
set.seed(1)
model.rf=randomForest(Satisfaction~.-Flight.Count-Flight.Distance-Gender-Age,data=data_train, mtry=5, importance=TRUE)

# Checking the accuracy
predTest.rf = predict(model.rf, data_test)
varImpPlot(model.rf)

confusion <- caret::confusionMatrix(predTest.rf, data_test$Satisfaction, mode = "prec_recall", positive = "Dissatisfied")
accuracy_model <- (confusion$table[1,1] + confusion$table[2,2])/sum(confusion$table)

confusion$table %>% 
  kable(caption = 'Real value/Prediction') %>% 
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F, position = "left")
Real value/Prediction
Dissatisfied Satisfied
Dissatisfied 838 44
Satisfied 36 258 
precision = confusion$table[1,1]/(confusion$table[1, 1]+confusion$table[1, 2])
recall = confusion$table[1,1]/(confusion$table[1, 1]+confusion$table[2, 1])
F1 = 2*precision*recall/(precision+recall)

Po = accuracy_model
a = ((confusion$table[1,1]+confusion$table[1,2])*(confusion$table[1,1]+confusion$table[2,1]))/sum(confusion$table)
b = ((confusion$table[2,1]+confusion$table[2,2])*(confusion$table[1,2]+confusion$table[2,2]))/sum(confusion$table)
Pe = (a+b)/sum(confusion$table)

Kappa = (Po-Pe)/(1-Pe)

metrics <- data.frame(Metrics = c("Accuracy", "Precision", "Recall", "F1", "Kappa"), Value = c(round(accuracy_model, 4), round(precision, 4), round(recall, 4), round(F1, 4), round(Kappa, 4)))

metrics %>% 
  kable(caption = 'Metrics of model quality') %>%

Model # 2: Logistic Regression

Now we will build a logistic regression model in otrder to predict whether the customer is satisfied by the services of not. For this model we will use the same predictors as for clusterisation so that we could compare the models further. These predictors are Flight.Distance, Flight.Count, D.Days, Online.Services, On.Board.Services and Airport.Services.

model_data <- data %>% select(Flight.Distance, Flight.Count, ddays, online_services, On.board.services, airport_services, Satisfaction)

colnames(model_data) <- c("Flight.Distance", "Flight.Count", "D.Days", "Online.Services", "On.Board.Services", "Airport.Services", "Satisfaction")

model_data$Satisfaction <- as.factor(model_data$Satisfaction)
library(caret)
set.seed(222)
d_test = createDataPartition(model_data$Satisfaction, p = 0.2, list = FALSE)
data_test = model_data[d_test,]
data_train = model_data[-d_test,]
logistic_model = glm(Satisfaction~., data = data_train, family = "binomial")
#summary(logistic_model)

model_results <- as.data.frame(logistic_model$coefficients)

The results of the model show that the effects of all factors on customers satisfaction are statistically significant.

Model 2: Evaluation

For the evaluation of the models quality we need to look at confusion matrix and the metrics of accuracy, precision, recall, F1 and Kappa.

test <- predict(logistic_model, data_test, type="response")
pred <- factor(ifelse(test > 0.5,"Satisfied","Dissatisfied"))
confusion <- caret::confusionMatrix(pred, data_test$Satisfaction, mode = "prec_recall", positive = "Dissatisfied")
accuracy_model <- (confusion$table[1,1] + confusion$table[2,2])/sum(confusion$table)

confusion$table %>% 
  kable(caption = 'Real value/Prediction') %>% 
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F, position = "left")
Real value/Prediction
Dissatisfied Satisfied
Dissatisfied 6780 1684
Satisfied 978 3030 
precision = confusion$table[1,1]/(confusion$table[1, 1]+confusion$table[1, 2])
recall = confusion$table[1,1]/(confusion$table[1, 1]+confusion$table[2, 1])
F1 = 2*precision*recall/(precision+recall)

Po = accuracy_model
a = ((confusion$table[1,1]+confusion$table[1,2])*(confusion$table[1,1]+confusion$table[2,1]))/sum(confusion$table)
b = ((confusion$table[2,1]+confusion$table[2,2])*(confusion$table[1,2]+confusion$table[2,2]))/sum(confusion$table)
Pe = (a+b)/sum(confusion$table)

Kappa = (Po-Pe)/(1-Pe)

metrics <- data.frame(Metrics = c("Accuracy", "Precision", "Recall", "F1", "Kappa"), Value = c(round(accuracy_model, 4), round(precision, 4), round(recall, 4), round(F1, 4), round(Kappa, 4)))

metrics %>% 
  kable(caption = 'Metrics of model quality') %>%

Accuracy of the model is quite good - about 79% of the customers were correctly predicted to be satisfied or not with the services. The value of recall is 0.87 which means that we were able to detect 87% of dissatisfied customers. The precision is slightly lower - among those customers who were classified as dissatisfied only 80% actually belong to this class. The F1 metrics which combines values of precision and recall equals 0.83 which is a good result. Kappa is positive and equals 0.53 which means that our model predicts the satisfaction of customers much better than if we assigned them these classes randomly.

Model 2: Important variables

In order to understand which variables are the most important for the prediction we should look at the table with odds ratio. The value of Odds Ratio shows how big is the effect of the variable: if the value is near 1, there is almost no effect, the value higher than 1 shows povitive effect and the value less than 1 shows negative effect.

coef(logistic_model) %>% exp() %>% round(2) %>% sort(decreasing = T) %>% kable(col.names = "Odds Ratio") %>% kable_styling("striped", full_width = F, position = "left")

From the table we can see that there are only two factors that have some effect on the customers satisfaction. Arport services have a small negative effect as the value of odds ratio for it is 0.71 which means that customers, who evaluated the airport services high, have lower chances to be satisfied (chances are multiplied by 0.71) - but this effect can be considered as a mistake of the model. However, On-board services have big positive effect - the odds ratio has value of 6.77 which means that customers, who gave high grade to this type of services have 6.77 times more chances to be generally satisfied. So, on board Services are the most important predictors of customers satisfaction.

Comparing the models

Disagreement:

The main disagreement between our models lays in the estimation of variables according to 5 different clusters in the first case and on the whole data in the second. Meaningfulness of variables vary from cluster to cluster and changes its places, being, actually, 5 models, and the impact of them is different from the second model.

Evaluation:

Models in the second case gave lower estimation metrics than from the first one (e.g.accuracy of 0.79 against 5 accuracies of 0.91-0.96), and monetary loss is also smaller in first models, which makes us incline to choose the first uplift policy.

Measures to increase loyalty passengers and marketing campaign

  • from Cluster 1: From clustering: think of the ways to improve On-board Services and Airport services. Maybe we should inspect the condition of the airports in cities from which the flights have been done and inspect the quality of the services in these planes and parent companies. A good idea is to load the form where the customers will leave the extended reviews of the flight (we can increase their will to do so by giving some bonuses, e.g.next flight discounts). They can show us where the problem exactly is. From modeling: push powers to increase the quality (and to attach customers attention) to comfortable seats, entertainment during flight, food and drinks, convenience of arrival time, ease of online booking and wellness of gate location.
  • from Cluster 2: From clustering: customers from this cluster mostly approve of all the type of services we provide. From modeling: push powers to increase entertainment during flight, comfortable seats, food and drinks, convenience of arrival time , location of the gate and legroom service
  • from Cluster 3: From clustering: We should pay special attentions for these people - they have already been with us for a while and seems like we might have lost their loyalty only recently. They gave us dramatically poor estimations of all types of services - a strong investigation should be conducted. For such strong reasons for disloyalty and dissatisfaction, we should make large steps for bringing these customers back to loyal. We can, for example, bring our firm regrets for the quality of the services and promise to figure it out, gift them a huge discount, maybe not for one but even for several further flights, maybe some merch and other pleasing moves. From modeling: push powers to increase comfortable seats, entertainment during flight, food and drinks, cleanliness of the airport and the presence of wi-fi service
  • from Cluster 4: From clustering: customers from this cluster highly approve of all the type of services we provide. From modeling: pay attention to entertainment during flight, comfortable seats, convinience of the arrival time, legroom service and cleanliness of the airport
  • from Cluster 5: From clustering: people from this cluster gave only bad estimations for long-distance flying. We should check the quality of planes and airports used in this particular voyages. It is quite a strong omission, so the strategy would be just as for the 3rd cluster. From modeling: entertainment during flight, comfortable seats, convenience of the arrival time, legroom service and cleanliness of the airport.

What-If analysis on Bayesian belief networks

We decided to find additional data on what actually influences Satisfaction rate in airline industry. We have revised some articles and found out the following: - Findings indicated that the quality of preflight, inflight and postflight services had a statistically significant effect on passenger satisfaction. - Customer satisfaction is directly related to the service quality provided by any airline company. - Quality service expectations in air travel are extremely important in consumers behaviour (Parasuraman et al., 1985) as they affect their satisfaction and also lead to buying decisions (Park et al, 2004).

Bibliography: Namukasa, Juliet. 2013. The Influence of Airline Service Quality on Passenger Satisfaction and Loyalty: The Case of Uganda Airline Industry. The TQM Journal 25. doi: 10.1108/TQM-11-2012-0092. Papageorgiou, N. 2016. Service Quality and Customer Satisfaction in Air Transportation. Retrieved December 14, 2020 (https://jotr.eu/index.php/volume15/189-service-quality-and-customer-satisfaction-in-air-transportation).

So, we are going to be taking such variables as Flight.Count, online_services,airport_services, On.board.services for our Bayesian network analisys. The assumption is very general and as per following: Higher values for all types of onboard, online and airport services will increase customer satisfaction level.

How can the cusomers react to out improvement policies? We expect from customers with higher satisfaction level tha the customers would bring more revenue to the market. The uplift policies regrading these very variables were described in the section above.

Business Metrics:

Lets count sticky factor and all metrics that go along with it. DAU, MAU, WAU will be counted for the year of 2013, because we rely on the latest available data of variable last_flight and our date of analysis is 2013-10-01.

data_dau_13 = data %>% filter(year(last_flight) == "2013") %>% group_by(last_flight) %>% dplyr::summarise(n = n())
dau = as.data.frame(mean(data_dau_13$n))
colnames(dau) <- "DAU"
data_wau_13 = data %>% filter(year(last_flight) == "2013") %>% group_by(week(last_flight)) %>% dplyr::summarise(n = n())
wau = as.data.frame(mean(data_wau_13$n))
colnames(wau) <- "WAU"
data_mau_13 = data %>% filter(year(last_flight) == "2013") %>% group_by(month(last_flight)) %>% dplyr::summarise(n = n())
mau = as.data.frame(mean(data_mau_13$n))
colnames(mau) <- "MAU"
a <- as.data.frame(cbind(stick_week = dau/wau * 100, stick_month = dau/mau * 100))
colnames(a) <- c("Weekly Sticky", "Monthly Sticky")
data_satisf = data %>% group_by(Satisfaction) %>% dplyr::summarise(n = n())
csat = data_satisf[2,2] / sum(data_satisf[,2])
csat_score = csat * 100
colnames(csat_score) <- "CSAT"
cbind(dau, wau, mau, a, csat_score) %>% kable() %>% kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", full_width = F, position = "left")
DAU WAU MAU Weekly Sticky Monthly Sticky CSAT
73.18356 504 2226 14.52055 3.287671 37.7951

We can see that:

  • DAU: on average 73 customers fly per day.
  • WAU: average 504 customers fly per week
  • MAU: on average 2226 customers fly per month.
  • The monthly Sticky is roughly 3.3% which means that on average 3% had a flight each day every month.
  • The Weekly Sticky is approximately 14.5% which which means that one average 14,5% had a flight each day every week.
  • the Customer Satisfaction Score is roughly 37,8%, which is not great.

Metrics by Segmentation:

Satisfaction by Cluster:

grid.arrange(clusters_satisfaction_plot, parrallel_plot, nrow = 2)

We see that most dissatisfied clusters are 1, 3 and 5, however 2 and 4 are also do not have the best division.

  • 1-st cluster: about 2/3 of the customers are dissatisfied. They stayed just for a while, has several flights and on medium distances. They have high estimation of online services, however thay poorly rate on board and airport services.
  • 2-nd cluster: we see that about half of the customers are dissatisfied. Ddays is very high, so they stayed long with us, had huge number of flights, fly for short distances, had high estimations of airport services, but were less satisfied with the online and on-board services
  • 3-rd cluster: almost 80% of the customers are disloyal. They were with us for some time, had medium amount of flights and flout on medium distances, dramatically poorly estimated airport services and on-board services, gave a little better estimation for online, but still very poor.
  • 4-th cluster: Approximately 50% of the users are disloyal. They are not long with us, have small amount of flights and distances are short and estimation here is maximum everywhere.
  • 5-th cluster: approximately 2/3 the users are disloyal. They stayed with us for a small time, had several flights for the longest distances, gave high rates for the services by airports and on board, but were extremely dissatisfied with online services.

Satisfaction-predictive model has worked well together with clusterization. All the models has performed with accuracy more than 90% - predicting 90% of values true, showing monetary loss no more than 6%.

Policy 1

  • from Cluster 1: From clustering: think of the ways to improve On-board Services and Airport services. Maybe we should inspect the condition of the airports in cities from which the flights have been done and inspect the quality of the services in these planes and parent companies. A good idea is to load the form where the customers will leave the extended reviews of the flight (we can increase their will to do so by giving some bonuses, e.g.next flight discounts). They can show us where the problem exactly is. From modeling: push powers to increase the quality (and to attach customers attention) to comfortable seats, entertainment during flight, food and drinks, convenience of arrival time, ease of online booking and wellness of gate location.
  • from Cluster 2: From clustering: customers from this cluster mostly approve of all the type of services we provide. From modeling: push powers to increase entertainment during flight, comfortable seats, food and drinks, convenience of arrival time , location of the gate and legroom service
  • from Cluster 3: From clustering: We should pay special attentions for these people - they have already been with us for a while and seems like we might have lost their loyalty only recently. They gave us dramatically poor estimations of all types of services - a strong investigation should be conducted. For such strong reasons for disloyalty and dissatisfaction, we should make large steps for bringing these customers back to loyal. We can, for example, bring our firm regrets for the quality of the services and promise to figure it out, gift them a huge discount, maybe not for one but even for several further flights, maybe some merch and other pleasing moves. From modeling: push powers to increase comfortable seats, entertainment during flight, food and drinks, cleanliness of the airport and the presence of wi-fi service
  • from Cluster 4: From clustering: customers from this cluster highly approve of all the type of services we provide. From modeling: pay attention to entertainment during flight, comfortable seats, convinience of the arrival time, legroom service and cleanliness of the airport
  • from Cluster 5: From clustering: people from this cluster gave only bad estimations for long-distance flying. We should check the quality of planes and airports used in this particular voyages. It is quite a strong omission, so the strategy would be just as for the 3rd cluster. From modeling: entertainment during flight, comfortable seats, convenience of the arrival time, legroom service and cleanliness of the airport.

Policy 2:

The most important factor here is Inflight entertainment, so it is the first thing we should pay attention to. The next influencing factor is seat comfort, so the company should work on this point in order to increase customers satisfaction. On board service, leg room service and wifi have lower effect on th satisfaction but still should be considered by the company.

Results of scenario analysis and policy implementation:

Scenario analysis is conducted on such variables as Flight.Count, online_services,airport_services, On.board.services according to:

Namukasa, Juliet. 2013. The Influence of Airline Service Quality on Passenger Satisfaction and Loyalty: The Case of Uganda Airline Industry. The TQM Journal 25. doi: 10.1108/TQM-11-2012-0092.

Papageorgiou, N. 2016. Service Quality and Customer Satisfaction in Air Transportation. Retrieved December 14, 2020 (https://jotr.eu/index.php/volume15/189-service-quality-and-customer-satisfaction-in-air-transportation).

Assumption:

Higher values for all types of onboard, online and airport services will increase customer satisfaction level.

graphviz.plot(bnStructure, shape = "ellipse")

Checking the assumption:

bn.fit.barchart(netw3$Satisfaction)

Our general conclusion is that by heightening the quality of onboard services, the clients, woth higher probability, will be satisfied with the condiions, regradless of conditions of online and airport services. still, we have to pay attention to other services in order to obtain the best result for satisfaction level.
